				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Apparently there's no CHR-RAM or NT/AT RAM that the NES can write to, the cart is actually wired to disable the internal VRAM (cartridges using 4-screen layout may do this too, if the memory for the 4 name tables is inside the cartridge), and the Raspberry Pi watches the PPU bus to supply the appropriate data every time the PPU tries to fetch data from VRAM.<br /><br />Even though attributes are limited to 16x16-pixel areas on the NES, the PPU actually fetches an attribute byte for every 8x1-pixel area, so if a mapper (like the MMC5) or a coprocessor (like the Raspberry Pi) keeps track of the memory fetches, it can supply different attribute data for each fetch, allowing for finer attribute distribution than the typical 16x16 chunks.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

						<table width="100%" cellspacing="0">
